Introduction

Part I: Data

In this project, our group will use the Marketing A/B Testing dataset which was collected from Kaggle. The dataset can be found here.

The dataset's documentation provides the following description:

This dataset contains a simple marketing campaign with experiment and control group for A/B testing.

The majority of the people have been exposed to ads (the experimental group), and a small portion of people (the control group) would instead see a Public Service Announcement (PSA) (or nothing) in the exact size and place the ad would normally be.

The idea of the dataset is to analyze the groups, find if the ads were successful, how much the company can expect to make from the ads, and if the difference between the groups is statistically significant.

The dataset contains the following variables:

  • index: Row index number (type: integer)
  • user_id: A unique numeric ID assigned to each user (type: integer)
  • test_group: Assigned test group "ad" if shown advertisement, and "psa" if only shown public service announcement. (type: string, converted to factor)
  • converted: TRUE if the user bought the product, FALSE otherwise (type: boolean)
  • total_ads: Number of ads seen by user (type: integer)
  • most_ads_day: Day the user saw the biggest amount of ads (type: string, converted to factor)
  • most_ads_hour: Hour of day that the user saw the biggest amount of ads (type: integer)

The dataset has 588,101 observations and 7 variables in total. There are no missing or NA values in the dataset.

Part II: Research Question

The question we will be attempting to answer is "Do the company's advertisements generate a meaningful increase in purchase conversion rates?".

We will attempt to discern if there is a statistically significance difference in conversion rates between both test groups. Within the dataset, we will use the converted variable to estimate conversion rates, and then compare these findings across groups identified in the test_group. The average converted variable will most likely be our response variable, with test_group acting as our explanatory variable.


Methods & Results

Part I: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

set.seed(301)

# Read, tidy, and summarise data from the web:
marketing_raw = read_csv(url("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cadenmchan/stat301/main/marketing_AB.csv"))

# Convert categorical variables into factors
marketing_raw$test_group = as.factor(marketing_raw$test_group)
marketing_raw$most_ads_day = as.factor(marketing_raw$most_ads_day)

# Remove NA values (should be none)
marketing = na.omit(marketing_raw) %>%
        select(-most_ads_day, -most_ads_hour)

# Divide total_ads by 2 if user converted, and 
# create a new feature, status, that combines the converted status and ad group
marketing = marketing %>%
    mutate(adj_total_ads = total_ads - total_ads * 0.5 * converted,
           status = as.factor(case_when(
               converted & test_group == "ad" ~ "AD: Converted",
               !converted & test_group == "ad" ~ "AD: Unconverted",
               converted & test_group == "psa" ~ "PSA: Converted",
               !converted & test_group == "psa" ~ "PSA: Unconverted"
            )))

We omitted the most_ads_day and most_ads_hour variables from our analysis. This is because they demonstrate the most frequent group for the ads shown to each individual, but lack information regarding the distribution of the ads (for example, were all ads shown on a specific day, or was one additional ad shown on that day?). In addition, we also do not have any information as to when individuals made purchases/conversions. Therefore, we believe that these variables omits a lot of related information that would make it useful or relevant to our analysis.

Plot 1: Total Converted Users (%)

First, the proportions of converted users for each test group (ad and control, psa) were displayed. Here, we see a difference in proportions but we are unsure about the significance of this difference. This is a good start to answering our research question.

Plot 2: Adjusted Conversion Rates (%)

Next, we compared the adjusted conversion rates for each test group. The adjusted conversion rate was calculated by dividing the total number of ads shown to converted users by two. Since our data does not show when a user was converted, a user who made a purchase after seeing a few ads would have a much lower, deflated, conversion rate contribution if they were shown multiple ads after. By dividing converted users' views in half, we can estimate that on average, a user saw roughly the same number of ads after they purchased as before. This adjustment was used to get a more accurate proxy of conversion rates.

Once again, we can see a difference across the two test groups, but we cannot make any accurate deductions as to the significance of these observed differences. Additional analysis could explore the statistical significance of this difference, and determine if the ads are more effective at converting users than PSAs.

Plot 3: Total Ads Shown by Test Group

After this, we created a boxplot that visualized the distribution and ranges of total_ads_shown for both the ad and control psa test groups. We can see that the number of ads shown in both groups appears to be skewed with a few users in each group being outliers with extremely high ad counts. However, across the two test groups, there seems to be no major discrepancies in the total number of ads shown to each individual. (There are more observations in the ads vs PSA group, but our dataset is large enough that this should not cause any issues in our analysis).

Plot 4: Adjusted Total Ads by Status

Four boxplots were generated to visualize the distribution and ranges of 'adj_total_ads' for users across four status groups. While minimal differences are observed in the ad and PSA groups, a notable distinction emerges in the number of ads shown to users who made a purchase, particularly in both test groups.

Two potential explanations exist for this observation. Firstly, a causal relationship may suggest that users who made a purchase were intentionally targeted with more ads. However, due to random group assignments, these ads may have been replaced by PSAs during the campaign, potentially influencing conversion rates. A conservative proxy for this effect involves reducing 'total_ads' by 50% for converted users, though a higher reduction is probable.

Alternatively, a confounding factor, such as time spent online, may influence both ad exposure and product purchase. For example, users who spend more time online could potentially be exposed to more ads, and also be more likely to purchase the product.Without product details and targeting strategies, identifying these factors is challenging.

Notably, the relationship between converted users and higher ad viewership appears consistent across ad and PSA groups. This suggests minimal impact on our methodology and results.

Part II: Methods: Plan

In order to explore our research question, we conducted three main pieces of analysis.

Part A: Two-Sample T-Test

The first methodology was an A/B Welch's Two-Sample T-Test, between the ad and psa test groups, to determine the significance of the two conversion rates between the groups.

The null hypothesis was that the average conversion rate is the same between test groups, with the alternative hypothesis being that the ad test group has a higher conversion rate than the psa test group.

In[4]:
# Performing Welch's T-test
test_result <- t.test(
    x = marketing %>% filter(test_group == "ad") %>% pull(converted),
    y = marketing %>% filter(test_group == "psa") %>% pull(converted),
    # testing whether the mean of x is greater than the mean of the y
    alternative = "greater", 
    # the Welch's T-test does not assume equal variances in the two groups
    var.equal = FALSE
)

Part B: Sequential A/B Testing

The second part of our methodology will introduce a simulated time dimension into our data, and explore the implication of A/B sequential testing.

Since the data we have currently does not have a time dimension, we artificially introduced an order of observations through randomization in order to conduct a simulation study. This effectively simulated a time dimension to our data, assuming there were no data trends over time. The observations were then grouped into batches based on time observed, and critical values were calculated over time. We used a sample size of 60,000, with 20 batches of 3,000 observations each.

We used the incremental_batch_t_test function to perform Welch's T-tests in batch increments. This function processes the dataset in fixed batches of a specified size. For each batch, it extracts and compares samples from both groups, aggregating the results up to and including that batch.

In[6]:
incremental_batch_t_test <- function(data, alpha) {
  results_df <- tibble(
    batch_id = integer(),
    statistic = numeric(),
    p_value = numeric(),
    sample_size = integer(),
  )

  # Group by batch_id
  data_grouped <- data %>% group_by(batch_id)

  for(batch in unique(data_grouped$batch_id)) {
    # Select samples up to and including the current batch_id
    ad_sample <- filter(data, test_group == "ad", batch_id <= batch)$converted
    psa_sample <- filter(data, test_group == "psa", batch_id <= batch)$converted

    # Check if both groups have data up to the current batch
    if (length(ad_sample) > 0 && length(psa_sample) > 0) {
      # Perform Welch's T-test
      t_test_results <- t.test(
          as.numeric(ad_sample), 
          as.numeric(psa_sample),
          alternative = "greater",
          var.equal = FALSE
      )
      results_df <- rbind(results_df, tibble(
        batch_id = batch,
        statistic = round(t_test_results$statistic, 4),
        p_value = round(t_test_results$p.value, 4),
        sample_size = length(ad_sample) + length(psa_sample)
      ))
    }
  }
  return (results_df)
}

Next, we evaluated these test-statistics using four different critical values, the unadjusted, Pocock, O'Brien-Fleming, and Bonferroni adjustments.

The sequential_crit_value_plot_with_correction function was used to visualize these critical values: This plot displays the critical values of each batch obtained from the Welch's T-tests. Each batch is plotted on the x-axis against its critical value on the y-axis. It visually compares the observed critical values against the threshold values for each correction method over time.

In[8]:
alpha = 0.05

unadjusted_crit <- qt(1 - 0.05 / 2, df = 599998)

bonferroni_crit<- qnorm(1 - alpha/number_of_tests)

design_pocock <- gsDesign(k = number_of_tests, #number of interim analysis planned
                          test.type = 1, # for one-sided tests
                          delta = 0, # default effect size
                          alpha = alpha, #type I error rate
                          beta = 0.2, # type II error rate
                          sfu = 'Pocock')
                          
pocock_crit<- design_pocock$upper$bound

design_of <- gsDesign(k = number_of_tests, #number of interim analysis planned
                      test.type = 1, # for one-sided tests
                      delta = 0, # default effect size
                      alpha = alpha, #type I error rate
                      beta = 0.2, # type II error rate
                      sfu = 'OF')
                          
OF_crit <- design_of$upper$bound

sequential_crit_value_plot_with_correction

Depending on the critical value adjustment selected, we would have stopped the experiment on different batches, with the unadjusted value being the least conservative, and the Bonferroni adjustment being the most conservative, with no stopping point within the 20 batches (60,000 observations) in our simulated sample.

For a company running ads, it makes the most sense to choose the adjustment method that allows us to stop as soon as possible, to reduce the costs of this experiment. However, we also do not want to jump to a false conclusion too early. To determine the ideal adjusted critical value to use, we can conduct an A/A test.

Part C: A/A Sequential Testing

To run our A/A test, we took 60,000 observations again, but randomly assigned them to the psa and ad test groups. As a result of this shuffling, we expect to see no statistically significant differences in conversion rates, and should theoretically never stop the experiment.

In[10]:
set.seed(1234) # For reproducibility

# Parameters
n_batches <- 20
batch_size <- 3000
total_subjects <- n_batches * batch_size

# Baseline conversion rates
conversion_rate <- 0.5

# Number of 'ad' subjects (rounded to nearest integer)
n_ad <- round(total_subjects * mean(marketing$test_group == "ad"))
n_psa <- round(total_subjects * mean(marketing$test_group == "psa"))

# Simulate data for a single distribution
total_conversions <- rbinom(total_subjects, 1, conversion_rate)

# Assign test groups with the specified proportion
# Ensure total subjects sum up correctly
test_groups <- c(rep('psa', n_psa), rep('ad', n_ad))

# Shuffle the test group assignments
shuffled_test_groups <- sample(test_groups)

# Create data frame
AA_data <- data.frame(
  batch_id = rep(1:n_batches, each = batch_size),
  subject_id = 1:total_subjects,
  test_group = shuffled_test_groups,
  converted = as.logical(total_conversions)
)


# Perform the same `incremental_batch_t_test` on the simulated A/A testing data.
AA_results <- incremental_batch_t_test(AA_data, alpha)

Discussion

Part A: Two-Sample T-Test

To answer our research question, "Do the company's advertisements generate a meaningful increase in purchase conversion rates?", we conducted an A/B two-sample t-test.

Based on the Welch's t-sample t-test conducted, we observed a t-statistic of 8.66 and a p-value of ~0 at the 0.05 significance level. Therefore, we can deduce that at the 0.05 significance level, the difference in means between our two test groups (ad and psa) is greater than zero. This implies that at the 95% confidence level there is indeed a statistically significant difference between conversion rates within the ad and psa (control) groups, and that the ad group has a significantly higher average conversion rate.

Part B: (Simulation Study) Sequential A/B Testing

Next, we randomly simulated a time dimension for each observation and assigned 60,000 observations to 20 batches of 3,000.

In[13]:
PartB_Results

We found that the unadjusted p-value would have us stop the earliest, followed by the O'Brien-Flemming, Pocock, and finally Bonferroni adjustments. A less conservative critical value allows us to stop earlier, saving experiment costs and time. However, an overly aggressive critical value could lead us to false conclusions. To identify the ideal adjustment, we conducted an A/A sequential test simulation study.

Part C: (Simulation Study) Sequential A/A Testing

Next, we simulated an A/A dataset by randomly assigning observations to the ad and psa test groups. We know that A/A testing should not find any statistically significant results.

In[14]:
PartC_Results

Here, we can see that all three of the adjusted values did not lead to an early stop in the A/A test, which indicates they are sufficient adjustments. Therefore, based on the results of the A/B and A/A tests, if we were to design a sequential test with early stopping, the O'Brien-Fleming adjustment would be the ideal adjustment method. A Pocock adjustment would also be viable, but a Bonferroni adjustment is likely to be too conservative and costly for our purpose.

Limitations and Areas for Additional Exploration

Our model could be improved by adding additional transformations to the data. For example, adjusted conversion rates could be used, such as adjusting for users being shown ads after making a purchase or taking into account the number of ads shown to each user. A larger, more comprehensive simulation study and sample size could also be conducted if additional computing resources were available.

The primary limitation of our experiment is that a significant portion of our data was artificially simulated, due to the dataset we had access to. Ideally, it would be good to validate these findings with additional, real-life data. Our findings could be further enhanced if applied and tested on real-world data containing time series data. Information about the number of ads a user saw before making a purchase, the dollar value/number of purchases, and the cost per ad impression could also be factored into further analysis to create a more robust and applicable model and analysis of advertising profitability for the company.
